rity and state violence in the wake of 11 September 2001. But what does his work have to say in an age characterised by financial crisis and political revolts? The 12 essays in this volume provide new perspectives on economy and political action by analysing Agamben’s recent work on government, his account of a non-statist politics and his relationship to the revolutionary tradition. It includes a new essay by Agamben himself, entitled ‘Capitalism as Religion’.ContributorsDaniel McLoughlin • Giorgio Agamben • Jason E. Smith • Jessica Whyte • Justin Clemens • Mathew Abbott • Miguel Vatter • Nicholas Heron • Sergei Prozorov • Simone Bignall • Steven DeCaroli  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aAbbott, Mathew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgamben, Giorgio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBignall, Simone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClemens, Justin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeCaroli, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeron, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLoughlin, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aProzorov, Sergei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Jason E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVatter, Miguel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhyte, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311078044440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474402651zCo-ac